    "summary": "On September 11, 1973, the Chilean military under General Augusto Pinochet overthrew the elected socialist government of President Salvador Allende in a coup supported by elements of the Chilean establishment and actively encouraged by the United States CIA and the Nixon administration. Allende had been elected in 1970 as the first democratically elected Marxist leader in Latin America, and his government had nationalized copper mines and other industries, alarming American business interests and Cold War strategists.\n\nAllende died during the coup — officially by suicide, according to subsequent investigations — as military aircraft bombed the presidential palace. In the aftermath, thousands of leftists, trade unionists, and suspected dissidents were arrested; many were taken to the National Stadium, tortured, and executed. Pinochet established a military dictatorship that ruled Chile until 1990, during which an estimated 3,000 people were killed, tens of thousands were tortured, and over 200,000 went into exile.\n\nThe Chilean coup became emblematic of Cold War-era American support for right-wing authoritarian regimes against leftist governments, regardless of their democratic legitimacy. Declassified documents confirmed extensive CIA involvement in destabilizing the Allende government before the coup. Chile's transition to democracy in 1990 and subsequent human rights trials placed the events of 1973 in sustained legal and historical scrutiny. Pinochet died in 2006 before being convicted of the human rights crimes committed under his regime.",
